### Encapsulation

Encapsulation bundles data and methods that operate on that data within a single unit (class), restricting direct access to some components.

---

### Data Hiding

```cpp
class BankAccount {
private:  // Hidden from outside
  double balance;

public:   // Public interface
  void deposit(double amount) {
    if (amount > 0) {
      balance += amount;
    }
  }

  bool withdraw(double amount) {
    if (amount > 0 && amount <= balance) {
      balance -= amount;
      return true;
    }
    return false;
  }

  double getBalance() const {
    return balance;
  }
};
```

---

### Getters and Setters

```cpp
class Person {
private:
  string name;
  int age;

public:
  string getName() const { return name; }
  void setName(const string& n) { name = n; }

  int getAge() const { return age; }
  void setAge(int a) {
    if (a > 0 && a < 150) age = a;
  }
};
```

---

### Benefits

| Benefit | Explanation |
|---------|-------------|
| Control | Validate data before setting |
| Flexibility | Change internal implementation freely |
| Security | Prevent unauthorized access |
| Maintainability | Isolate changes to class internals |

---

> **Key Point:** Use `private` for data members and provide public `getter`/`setter` methods for controlled access. This is a fundamental OOP principle that improves code maintainability.

codeExample:
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Employee {
private:
  int id;
  double salary;

public:
  void setId(int empId) { id = empId; }
  int getId() const { return id; }

  void setSalary(double s) {
    if (s >= 0) salary = s;
  }

  double getSalary() const { return salary; }
};

int main() {
  Employee emp;
  emp.setId(101);
  emp.setSalary(50000);
  cout << "ID: " << emp.getId() << ", Salary: $" << emp.getSalary() << endl;
  return 0;
}
